APIs

.application programming interface
.enable communication and efficient data sharing between applications and systems
    .enable seamless interaction between applications, platforms, and services
    .power everyday features such as weather updates, payments, and e-commerce payments 

    take a request > send to server > retrieves the data > returns the response 
.critical to building scalable, and connected systems 


Need:
.reusability - avoid reinventing the wheel by leveraging existing APIs
.efficiency - save development time by integrating ready made functionalities 
.scalability - enable modular, distributed systems that can grow easily
.integration - connect multiple platforms web, mobile, IoT, or analytics 
.automation - allow machines to talk to machines without manual input


How they work:
.operate through a request response cycle between a client and server 
    request - clients sends a request to an API endpoint (URI)
    processing - API forwards the request to the server 
    response - server processes and sends back the requested data 
    delivery - API returns servers response to the client 

.this communication happens over the HTTP/s protocol, with additional security via headers, tokens, or cookies 


Types of API Architectures
.define how systems communicate and exchange data
.they offer different levels of flexibility, performance, and structure based on application needs 

1. REST - representational state transfer 
.uses HTTP methods for communication - GET, POST, PUT, DELETE 
.data format - JSON, XML


2. SOAP - simple object access protocol 
.requires XML based messaging for communication 
.XML data format 


3. GraphQL 
.lets clients fetch only the data they need 
.JSON data format 


4. gRPC 
.high performance framework for Protocol Buffers (Protobuf)
.binary data format 



Types 
.categorized according to their accessibility, usage, and purpose 

.web - accessible via the internet using HTTP; widely used for web apps   - REST, GraphQL 
.local - used within a local environment or OS  - Windows, .NET, TAPI
.program - allow remote programs to appear local via Remote Procedure Calls  -  SOAP, XML-RPC
.internal - used privately within an organization  -  internal microservices 
.partner - shared with specific business partners  - Payment Gateway APIs
.open (public) - available for general developer purpose 


REST APIs
.follow the constraints of REST architecture allowing interaction with RESTful web services 
.defines a set of functions that clients use to access server data 
    get - retrieve a record 
    put - update a record
    post - create a record 
    delete - delete a record 


API Integration
.connects two or more systems so they can exchange data automatically 
    e.g connecting my e-commerce store to a payment gateway 
        syncing CRM software with a marketing platform 


API Testing
.ensures that APIs function as intended focusing on logic, performance, and security rather than UI 


Types 
